.TH "WORKERGLOBALSCOPE.IMPORTSCRIPTS" "3JS" "January 26, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
WorkerGlobalScope.importScripts \- WorkerGlobalScope: importScripts()
method
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is only available in Web Workers.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] The parameters passed to this method represent the
URLs of classic scripts to be imported into a worker.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by having a Content Security Policy (CSP)
that restricts the locations from which scripts can be loaded, and by
always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings
and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]importScripts()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]WorkerGlobalScope\f[R] interface synchronously imports one or more
scripts into the scope of a classic worker (a worker constructed from a
classic script).
.PP
Note that the method cannot be used in module workers, which instead
load dependencies using \f[CR]import\f[R] statements.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
importScripts(url0)
importScripts(url0, url1)
importScripts(url0, url1, /* \&..., */ urlN)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]urlN\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instance or a string representing the URL
of the script to be imported.
The URL may be absolute or relative.
If the URL is relative, it is relative to the worker entry script\(cqs
URL.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]NetworkError\f[R]
Imported scripts were served without a \f[CR]text/javascript\f[R] media
(MIME) type or without one of the permitted legacy JavaScript MIME
types.
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R]
Thrown if any URL cannot be resolved.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the current \f[CR]WorkerGlobalScope\f[R] is a module (use
\f[CR]import\f[R] instead).
It may also happen if any parameter is not a \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R]
and the site is enforcing trusted types.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]importScripts()\f[B]\f[R] method synchronously imports
one or more scripts into the scope of a classic worker.
.PP
Unlike the initial classic module script, which must be same\-origin
with its document, this method can import cross\-origin scripts unless
blocked by a \f[CR]Cross\-Origin\-Resource\-Policy\f[R], Content
Security Policy (CSP), or some other security mechanism.
Note that because classic scripts are fetched in \f[CR]no\-cors\f[R]
mode, they can be fetched cross\-origin even if the server does not set
the appropriate CORS headers.
.SS Security considerations
The parameters specify scripts to be imported into the scope of a
classic worker.
If the URLs for the scripts are provided by a user, this is a possible
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
It is extremely risky to accept and execute arbitrary URLs from
untrusted origins.
A website should control what scripts that are allowed to run using a
Content Security Policy (CSP) with the \f[CR]script\-src\f[R] directive
(or a fallback defined in \f[CR]default\-src\f[R]).
This can restrict scripts to those from the current origin, or a
specific set of origins, or even particular files.
.PP
If you\(cqre using this property and enforcing trusted types (using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive), you will need to
always assign \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to reject or modify the URL before it is injected.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
If you had some functionality written in a separate script called
\f[CR]foo.js\f[R] in the same directory as \f[CR]worker.js\f[R], you
could import it into the worker using the following line:
.IP
.EX
importScripts(\(dqfoo.js\(dq);
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]importScripts()\f[R] and \f[CR]self.importScripts()\f[R] are
effectively equivalent \(em both represent \f[CR]importScripts()\f[R]
being called from inside the worker\(cqs inner scope.
.PP
Note that in the next section we show you how to pass a
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instead of a string.
This was omitted in this example for brevity, but is recommended in
production code.
.SS Using TrustedScriptURL
To mitigate the risk of XSS, we should always assign
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances to each of the parameters.
We also need to do this if we\(cqre enforcing trusted types for other
reasons and we want to allow some script sources that have been
permitted (for example, by \f[CR]CSP: script\-src\f[R]).
.PP
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the trusted types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we create a \f[CR]TrustedTypePolicy\f[R] that defines a
\f[CR]createScriptURL()\f[R] method for transforming input strings into
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances.
.PP
For the purpose of this example we\(cqll assume that we want to allow a
predefined set of URLs in the \f[CR]scriptAllowList\f[R] array and log
any other scripts.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] scriptAllowList = [
  \f[I]// Some list of allowed URLs\f[R]
];
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqscript\-url\-policy\(dq, {
  createScriptURL(input) {
    \f[B]if\f[R] (scriptAllowList.includes(input)) {
      \f[B]return\f[R] input; \f[I]// allow the script\f[R]
    }
    console.log(\(gaScript not in scriptAllowList: ${input}\(ga);
    \f[B]return\f[R] \(dq\(dq; \f[I]// Block the script\f[R]
  },
});
.EE
.PP
Then we use the \f[CR]policy\f[R] object to create a
\f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R] object from a potentially unsafe input string:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious string\f[R]
\f[I]// We won\(aqt be including untrustedScript in our scriptAllowList array\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedScript = \(dqhttps://evil.example.com/import_worker.js\(dq;

\f[I]// Create a TrustedScriptURL instance using the policy\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedScriptURL = policy.createScriptURL(untrustedScript);
.EE
.PP
The \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] object can now be used when importing
the script in a classic worker:
.IP
.EX
importScripts(trustedScriptURL);
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
